      <p>First, we assess the computational complexity of IBD detection methods. We recorded the computation times for different data sets and the following methods: HapFABIA, fastIBD (<xref rid="gkt1013-B26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>), PLINK (<xref rid="gkt1013-B22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>), GERMLINE (<xref rid="gkt1013-B27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>), DASH (<xref rid="gkt1013-B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>), fastPHASE (<xref rid="gkt1013-B25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>), RELATE (<xref rid="gkt1013-B23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>) and MCMC (<xref rid="gkt1013-B34" ref-type="bibr">34</xref>). <xref ref-type="table" rid="gkt1013-T2">Table 2</xref> reports the computational times. fastPHASE, RELATE and MCMC are not feasible for IBD detection in large data sets because of their extremely high computational complexity. To extract IBD segments from chromosome 1 in the data of the 1000 Genomes Project, RELATE would require 6.5 CPU years, and both fastPHASE and MCMC even more. GERMLINE and HapFABIA are the fastest IBD detection methods.
